subsection.p:
Now integrate around the unit circle C:\quad x=\cos t,\qquad y=\sin t,\qquad 0\le t\le2\pi, oriented counterclockwise. Then dx=-\sin t\,dt, \qquad dy=\cos t\,dt. The numerator becomes
-y\,dx+x\,dy \amp= -(\sin t)(-\sin t\,dt)+(\cos t)(\cos t\,dt) \amp= \sin^2t\,dt+\cos^2t\,dt \amp= dt.
The denominator is x^2+y^2=1. Therefore \boxed{\oint_C\alpha = \int_0^{2\pi}dt = 2\pi.}

